From Mary Shafer Subject Re Inner Ear Problems from Too Much Flying On Apr GMT Vida Morkunas said Vida Can one develop inner ear problems from too much flying I hear Vida that pilots and steward esses have a limit as to the maximum Vida number of flying hours what are these limits What are the Vida main problems associated with too many long haul over hours Vida trips The crew rest requirements are to prevent undue The cockpit crew pilot limits are somewhat more stringent than the cabin crew limits for this Crew rest requirements address amount of time on duty plus rest A tired crew is an accident prone The only limits I know of for inner ear problems are in military aircraft which are frequently unpressurized or less reliably Not being able to clear the ears renders aircrew members DNIF duties not involving flying or grounded until the ears Flying can accentuate problems if ears don't If you don't have big pressure changes you may not know that you've got a But if you zip up to or ft the usual cabin altitude in an airliner and then back down to sea level you may discover a Ears don't clear readily because of allergies colds infections and anatomical The last won't change the first three Medication decongestants or antihistimines usually can Chewing gum sucking hard candy or a bottle for babies yawning these will help all four Mary Shafer DoD KotFR NASA Dryden Flight Research Facility Edwards CA Of course I don't speak for NASA A MiG at your six is better than no MiG at Unknown US fighter pilot